  "prompt": "How can I remove the HTC One X System folder, which still appears on my Windows 7 list of devices?",
  "response": "The \"HTC One X System\" entry you see in your Windows 7 devices list is a remnant of the HTC Sync Manager (or similar software) installation and drivers. It doesn't actually reflect a physical folder on your PC.  Here's how to remove it:\n\n**1. Uninstall HTC Sync Manager (or Similar Software):**\n\n*   **Go to Control Panel -> Programs -> Programs and Features.**\n*   Look for \"HTC Sync Manager\" or any similar HTC software you might have installed (e.g., \"HTC Driver Installer\").\n*   **Uninstall** the program.  Follow the on-screen prompts.  Reboot your computer after uninstallation.\n\n**2. Device Manager - The More Reliable Method:**\n\nThis is the most effective method as it targets the driver installation directly.\n\n*   **Open Device Manager:**\n    *   Click the **Start** button.\n    *   Type `devmgmt.msc` into the search box and press Enter.\n*   **Find the HTC Device:**\n    *   Expand \"Portable Devices\" or \"Other Devices\" or even \"Unknown Devices\".  Look carefully; the HTC One X might be under any of these.  If you previously connected the phone, it might also be listed under a more specific name reflecting the model.\n    *   If you find a device that sounds like the HTC One X but shows a yellow exclamation mark (!) or some other error, that's a good candidate.\n*   **Uninstall the Driver:**\n    *   **Right-click** on the device entry (e.g., \"HTC One X,\" or the one with the error).\n    *   Select \"**Uninstall**.\"\n    *   **Crucially:**  A dialog box will appear.  **Check the box that says \"Delete the driver software for this device.\"**  This is essential to completely remove the lingering files.\n    *   Click \"OK\" to uninstall.\n*   **Repeat** the process if there are multiple HTC-related entries under different categories in Device Manager.\n*   **Reboot your computer.**\n\n**3. Show Hidden Devices (If You Can't Find It):**\n\nSometimes the device is hidden.\n\n*   **Open Device Manager:** (as described above)\n*   Click on the **View** menu.\n*   Select \"**Show hidden devices**.\"\n*   Now, expand the categories again (especially \"Portable Devices,\" \"Other Devices,\" and \"Unknown Devices\") to see if the HTC One X entry appears.  If so, proceed with the \"Uninstall the Driver\" steps above.\n\n**4. Clean Up Driver Registry Entries (Advanced - Use with Caution!):**\n\nThis is an advanced step and can be risky if done incorrectly. **Back up your registry before proceeding!** Incorrect modifications to the registry can cause system instability.\n\n*   **Open Registry Editor:**\n    *   Click the **Start** button.\n    *   Type `regedit` into the search box and press Enter.\n*   **Navigate to Driver Registry Keys:**  Look for the following registry locations, but **be *extremely* careful not to delete anything you're not sure about.**\n    *   `HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\Software\\HTC`\n    *   `HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SOFTWARE\\HTC`\n    *   `HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Enum\\USB` (Look within the `USB` key for entries related to HTC or the One X.  Be very cautious here; USB devices are very common.)\n*   **Delete HTC-Related Entries (Carefully!):**\n    *   If you find any entries that clearly refer to \"HTC One X\" or \"HTC\" (under the paths above), you can **right-click** on the **folder** (key) and select \"Delete.\"  Be absolutely sure you're deleting the correct entry before proceeding.\n*   **Reboot your computer.**\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Why is it still there?** The entry persists because Windows remembers the device and the drivers associated with it. Even if you physically disconnect the phone, the drivers remain unless you explicitly remove them.\n*   **\"Safely Remove Hardware\" icon?**  The HTC One X typically doesn't appear in the \"Safely Remove Hardware\" icon because it's not treated as a removable storage device in the same way as a USB flash drive.\n*   **Reinstallation:** If you ever want to connect your HTC One X to your computer again, you'll likely need to reinstall HTC Sync Manager (or whatever software you were using) or download the necessary USB drivers from the HTC website.  By clearing all these entries, you are completely removing the driver from your PC.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to remove the \"HTC One X System\" entry from your list of devices. Remember to proceed with caution, especially when editing the registry. Good luck!\n",
